In [[Inca mythology]], '''Mama Cora Ocllo'''<ref>{{cite web|title=EL PRIMER NVEVA CORÓNICA|url=http://base.kb.dk/manus_pub/cv/manus/ManusPage.xsql?nnoc=manus_pub&p_ManusId=253&p_PageNo=124&p_Lang=main&p_Mode=ocr|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720030905/http://base.kb.dk/manus_pub/cv/manus/ManusPage.xsql?nnoc=manus_pub&p_ManusId=253&p_PageNo=124&p_Lang=main&p_Mode=ocr|archivedate=2011-07-20|df=}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɒ|k|j|oʊ}}, '''Mama Ocllo''',  '''Mama Ogllo''', '''Mama Oello'''<ref>{{cite book|last=Bancroft|first=byHubert Howe|title=The works of Hubert Howe Bancroft the native races : vol. IV, antiquities.|year=1980|publisher=A.L. Bancroft|location=San Francisco|isbn=0665141556|page=296}}</ref> (in Hispanicized spellings), '''Mama Oella''', '''Mama Oullo''', '''Mama Occlo''' (spellings resulting from bad [[Optical character recognition|OCR]]),<ref>{{cite book|last=Edwardes|first=Marian|title=A dictionary of non-classical mythology|year=1912|publisher=J.M. Dent & Sons|location=London|page=113}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Bingham|first=Ann|title=South and Meso-American mythology A to Z|year=2004|publisher=Facts on file|location=New York|isbn=0816048894|page=79}}</ref> '''Mama Okllo'''  or '''Mama Uqllu''' ([[Quechua language|Quechua]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Dean|first=Carolyn|title=A culture of stone : Inka perspectives on rock|year=2010|publisher=Duke University Press|location=Durham, NC|isbn=9780822347910|page=88}}</ref> was deified as a [[Mother Goddess|mother]] and [[fertility goddess]].<ref name=Rom>{{cite book|last=Siquijor|first=Rom|title=Inkari : the sacred prophecy of the inca kings.|publisher=Palibrio|location=[S.l.]|isbn=1617648736}}</ref> In one legend she was a daughter of [[Inti]] and [[Mama Killa]], and in another the daughter of [[Viracocha]] (Wiraqucha) and [[Inca mythology|Mama Qucha]].<ref name=Bingham>{{cite book|last=Bingham|first=Ann|title=South and Meso-American mythology A to Z|year=2004|publisher=Facts on file|location=New York|isbn=0816048894|page=68}}</ref>  She was the sister and wife of [[Manco Cápac]] (Manqu Qhapaq)<ref name=Gamboa>de Gamboa, P.S., 2015, History of the Incas, Lexington, {{ISBN|9781463688653}}</ref>{{rp|28–36}} and discovered [[Cusco]] with him.<ref name=Julien>{{cite book|last=Julien|first=Catherine|title=Reading Inca history|year=2000|publisher=University of Iowa Press|location=Iowa City|isbn=9781587294112|page=64}}</ref><ref name=Coulter>{{cite book|last=Coulter|first=Charles Russell|title=Encyclopedia of ancient deities|year=2000|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=9780786403172|page=304|author2=Turner, Patricia}}</ref> She taught the [[Inca]] women [[weaving (mythology)|the art of spinning thread]].<ref name=Stanton>{{cite book|last=Stanton|first=editors: Janet Parker, Julie|title=Mythology : myths, legends & fantasies|year=2006|publisher=Struik|location=Cape Town, South Africa|isbn=1770074538|page=505}}</ref>

